1. Why use GROMACS for protein–protein MD?

GROMACS (GROningen MAchine for Chemical Simulations) remains one of the most popular MD engines, and for protein–protein systems, it offers several advantages:
Speed and Efficiency: Can simulate large protein–protein complexes (50k–200k atoms) efficiently, especially with GPU acceleration, while maintaining high numerical accuracy.
Open-Source and Free: No licensing restrictions, ideal for academic and collaborative projects.
Flexibility and Compatibility: Supports a wide range of force fields, solvent models, constraints, and topology formats. Handles complex systems including homo- and hetero-dimers, multi-domain proteins, and membrane-bound complexes.
Strong Community and Documentation: Extensive tutorials for protein–protein simulations, forums, and active development for bug fixes and performance improvements.
Reproducibility: Deterministic algorithms and checkpointing ensure that your long simulations can be reliably reproduced—a must for publications.

