| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| **Performance**             | Extremely fast on CPU/GPU; optimized for large protein complexes    | Fast, but slower for >100k atoms          | Efficient, hardware-dependent | Very fast on GPUs; license required for full features |
| **Ease of Use**             | Open-source, strong tutorials & community                           | Well-documented, academic-focused         | Script-heavy                  | GUI-friendly, less flexible in scripts                |
| **Protein-Protein Support** | Native support; no special ligand tools needed                      | Limited multi-chain protocols             | Good, but needs scripts       | Mostly GUI-driven, less customizable                  |
| **Reproducibility**         | Checkpoints, deterministic algorithms                               | Good, but version-dependent               | Good                          | Proprietary methods can limit reproducibility         |
| **Flexibility**             | Highly flexible (constraints, thermostats, barostats, force fields) | Moderate; mostly AMBER FF                 | Flexible but script-heavy     | Less flexible for non-standard setups                 |
| **Cost**                    | Free & open-source                                                  | Free for academic; license for commercial | Free                          | Commercial license for full features                  |

2. Why CHARMM36-JUL2022 Force Field for protein–protein MD?

Choosing the right force field (FF) is critical. For protein–protein simulations, CHARMM36-JUL2022 is ideal:
State-of-the-Art Protein Accuracy: Latest backbone and side-chain parameters improve secondary structure maintenance in long MD, reducing unphysical distortions in loops, helices, and β-sheets.
Multi-Chain Compatibility: Handles chain–chain interactions reliably, important for homo- and hetero-dimers.
Ion and Solvent Treatment: Improved treatment of ions and TIP3P water ensures realistic electrostatics at protein–protein interfaces.
Stability in EM and MD: Less prone to LINCS or extreme force failures, which is critical in large protein complexes with multiple interfaces.
Future-Proof for Advanced Studies: Supports long trajectories, enhanced sampling, and free energy calculations of binding interfaces.

