3. Tips & Tricks Specific to Protein–Protein MD

a. Pre-processing with PyMOL:
Check chain IDs, fix missing residues, and remove non-biological ligands or crystallographic water that might interfere.
Align and merge chains if docking (ClusPro, HADDOCK) introduces chain mismatches.

b. Protonation States & Histidines:
Use pdb2gmx carefully; assign histidine protonation at the interface to avoid unphysical hydrogen bonding.

c. Solvation Box:
Use triclinic box with at least 1.0–1.2 nm buffer from any protein atom to the box edge.
Ensure correct ionic strength (e.g., 0.15 M NaCl) for physiological relevance, especially at the interface.

d. Energy Minimization & Restraints:
First minimize with position restraints on backbone to stabilize interfaces.
Gradually release restraints before equilibration.

e. Equilibration:
NVT → NPT with mild restraints.
Monitor RMSD of both individual chains and the interface separately.

f. Production MD:
Save trajectories frequently (10–50 ps) to capture interface dynamics.
Consider long simulations (100–500 ns+) to observe slow rearrangements.

g. Analysis Beyond RMSD/RMSF:
Inter-chain hydrogen bonds and salt bridges.
Interface surface area (SASA).
Distance distributions of key interacting residues.
Cluster analysis of interface conformations.


Download GROMACS: https://manual.gromacs.org/current/download.html
Note: Always prefer CHARMM36-JUL2022 over older releases (e.g., March 2019) for improved protein–protein interface modeling.
